<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="103" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="36.[227,372,716,742]" box="[227,372,716,742]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,372,716,742]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,372,716,742]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[227,1437,763,1001]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">
<typeStatus box="[227,336,763,789]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">Holotype</typeStatus>
MB.C.30486 is a rather well-preserved, almost completely chambered specimen with 
<quantity box="[1354,1437,763,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.6" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" unit="mm" value="76.0">76 mm</quantity>
conch diameter, from which the last, poorly preserved segment was removed before photography (
<figureCitation box="[235,328,833,859]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="36.[227,270,2001,2027]" captionTargetBox="[232,1431,1425,1963]" captionTargetId="figure-272@36.[227,1437,1421,1969]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Fig. 29. Maccoyoceras concavum sp. nov., holotype MB.C.30486 (Wendt and Kaufmann 1995 Coll.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6885268" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6885268/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). The specimen allows the study from both sides. The conch is extremely discoidal (ww/ dm =0.32) and subevolute (uw/dm =0.41) with a very high coiling rate (WER =2.35). The whorl profile is compressed hexagonal (ww/wh =0.93) and widest at the rounded umbilical margin. The flanks stand almost parallel and converge barely towards the angular ventrolateral shoulder that separates the flanks from the weakly concave venter. The umbilical wall is convexly rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[226,1436,1039,1207]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">
Two ontogenetic stages of the ornament development can be separated: up to 
<quantity box="[1123,1205,1040,1066]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" unit="mm" value="17.0">17 mm</quantity>
conch diameter, six coarse, crenulated spiral lines on the flank are the dominant elements in the juvenile stage. Thereafter, fine but sharp narrow-standing growth lines with weakly biconvex course form the ornament on the flanks, but the venter bears very delicate growth lines with a deep ventral sinus. The suture line shows a shallow ventral lobe and a shallow lateral lobe. The siphuncle is almost central.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="104" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="36.[227,341,1246,1272]" box="[227,341,1246,1272]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,341,1246,1272]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,341,1246,1272]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[227,1436,1292,1389]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[227,525,1293,1318]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Maccoyoceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="concavum" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[227,525,1293,1318]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">Maccoyoceras concavum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[533,625,1293,1319]" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has conch proportions very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Korn, Miao &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[1187,1372,1293,1318]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Maccoyoceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pentagonum">
<emphasis box="[1187,1372,1293,1318]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">M. pentagonum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the contemporaneous ‘Dalle à 
<taxonomicName box="[593,737,1328,1353]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Prolecanitidae" genus="Merocanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="36" pageNumber="103" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[593,737,1328,1353]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="103">Merocanites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ of Timimoun. However, the new species differs from this and from the other species of the genus by the concave venter.
</paragraph>
